        "title": "why unexpected behaviour for conditional operator",
        "body": "<p>I have a piece of code like follows<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Test{\n               public static void main(String[] args) {\n                  System.out.println(true?false:true == true?false:true);\n                                                -----------------------\n               }\n            }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The output is <code>false<\/code>. If you are using Eclipse you get a wavy (dashed here) line and warning like \"Comparing identical expressions\". Note the start of the wavy line.<\/p>\n\n<p>I changed the code to the following<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>              public class Test{\n               public static void main(String[] args) {\n                  System.out.println((true?false:true) == (true?false:true));\n                                     ---------------------------------------\n               }\n            }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The output is <code>true<\/code>. If you are using Eclipse you get a wavy (dashed here) line and warning like \"Comparing identical expressions\". Note the start of the wavy line now.<\/p>\n\n<p>Why the difference?<\/p>\n",
